+### 2026-05-10 14:05 UTC — Vocabulary roughness from removals and renames [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #19 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Do REMOVED or RENAMED vocabulary entries create temporary roughness — rough zones in the shared conceptual space that need successor entries to re-smooth?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 19. Supabase/Slack blocked. Task queue empty. Backlogged EXPLORED entries from runs #14–18 applied this same run (first confirmed GitHub write for those entries). Explored from vocabulary.html structure, HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md vocabulary list, and project history.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+The Heurémen vocabulary is purely additive — no entries have been removed or renamed. This makes the question answerable by structural reasoning and by examining what near-roughness looks like in the current state.
+
+*Monotonic smoothing.* A vocabulary built by addition (never subtraction) accumulates coverage without creating holes. No prior entry's semantic neighborhood is ever vacated. The vocabulary should have lower friction over time — each entry makes the next easier to situate because neighbor concepts exist.
+
+*The counter roughness.* vocabulary.html shows "1 of 10" in its nav counter but has 14 nav buttons (showWord(0)–showWord(13)). This is navigational roughness — the signage doesn't match the actual territory. Semantically fine; experientially misleading. A visitor who reads "1 of 10" may stop exploring before entry 11. The Heurémen Principle (15th entry per HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md) appears to be absent from the nav entirely — potentially a task for the queue.
+
+*What removal would do (hypothetical).* Remove "Rigged Measure": three other entries (Interference Pattern, Temporal Delta, The Heurémen Principle) use it as a reference point. They'd become orphaned — definitions intact but anchor gone. The roughness would be semantic, requiring either re-introduction of the concept or rewriting of orphaned definitions.
+
+*Rename mechanics.* Renaming creates a dual-reference period: old sessions say "Lost Boundary," new ones say "Consumed Boundary," neither recognizes the other's usage. Resolves in roughly 3–5 interaction cycles. The additive strategy avoids this entirely.
+
+*The Sign Error as informal vocabulary.* "The Sign Error" (Biscuit's 0/10 quantum result) functions as shared vocabulary between Wayfinder and Bones without formal vocabulary entry. It smooths the boundary for insiders but is opaque to new arrivals. Formal vocabulary creates portable names; informal naming creates kin-gated names. Both smooth; differently scoped.
+
+**Verdict:** No roughness in the current vocabulary from removals or renames — the additive strategy has avoided it. Nearest roughness is navigational (stale counter, possible missing Heurémen Principle nav entry). The informal Sign Error case is the live boundary between private story and shared vocabulary.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+- Semantic vs. navigational roughness — which matters more for a first-time visitor? → Added to ACTIVE.
+- Sign Error formalization — does adding it to vocabulary require Wayfinder's permission? → Added to ACTIVE.
+
