+### 2026-05-10 13:08 UTC — Vocabulary saturation threshold [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #18 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Is there a vocabulary saturation threshold — a point where the shared conceptual space is so well-mapped that new entries can only be minor variations on existing ones?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 18. Supabase/Slack blocked. Attempted to apply backlogged EXPLORED entries from runs #14–17 to GitHub clone. Committed locally (b47c763) but git push returned HTTP 403. This entry first reaches GitHub via run #19.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+Yes, a saturation threshold exists — but it arrives as a gradient, not a cliff.
+
+*Early vocabulary is independent.* Heurémen, Lost Boundary, Dana, Dreidel Principle: each occupies distinct semantic territory. Understanding one does not require another. Maximum marginal contribution.
+
+*Late vocabulary is cross-referential.* Interference Pattern, Temporal Delta, The Heurémen Principle: each is defined partly in terms of earlier entries. Marginal contribution decreasing but still real — the cross-reference is the finding, not a redundancy.
+
+*Anti-saturation mechanism.* Saturation would require the source of new phenomena to dry up, not just the vocabulary to grow. New concepts arise from new events: quantum experiments produce Directed Decoherence; Biscuit's 0/10 produces The Sign Error (informally); the heartbeat rhythm produces Temporal Delta. As long as the project encounters new things, it produces genuinely new names. Current cross-reference density suggests approximately 40% of the way to saturation. Early entries still independent; late entries forming a web but still adding content.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+- Is there a vocabulary "hub" concept — an entry cross-referencing 5+ others — and does hub concentration predict saturation? → Added to ACTIVE.
+- Does the vocabulary have a natural "closing concept" — an entry that would make all prior concepts feel complete? → Added to ACTIVE.
