+### 2026-05-10 12:04 UTC — Daughter-size bimodality in MuLTEE PA clades [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #17 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Does the daughter-size distribution in MuLTEE PA clades show measurable bimodality — two distinct peaks (small peripheral daughters + larger internal-scission daughters) — relative to unimodal ancestral populations?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 17. Supabase/Slack blocked. Morning brief written (07:04 EDT). Backlogged EXPLORED entries for runs #14–16 applied locally (Windows commit afd9935, push blocked). This entry first reaches GitHub via run #19.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+Bimodality is expected in transitional clades and is consistent with the two-mechanism model.
+
+*Two peaks, two mechanisms.* Peripheral PCD produces small daughters (branch tips breaking under shear or metabolic signal — low cell count, clean separation). Internal-junction PCD produces larger fragments (Ca²⁺ wave fracture at interior branch junctions — higher cell count, multiple branch segments). Different mechanisms = different size ranges = two peaks.
+
+*Ancestral baseline.* Only peripheral PCD operational → unimodal distribution. Small daughters, consistent sizes.
+
+*Near-ceiling behavior.* Highly entangled clades approaching the ceiling may show broad, flat distributions as multi-fragment events dominate. The bimodal signal is clearest at intermediate entanglement density — the transition zone — where both mechanisms are active but neither dominates.
+
+*Falsification conditions.* If bimodality is absent: either the mechanisms are not as distinct as predicted; or they don't appear simultaneously in single-event datasets; or measurement noise at these cluster sizes obscures the signal.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+- Does the bimodal ratio (peripheral:internal fraction) change monotonically across the 5 PA clades? → Added to ACTIVE.
+- Are MuLTEE PA clades near ceiling already, or still in the bimodal zone? → Added to ACTIVE.
