+### 2026-05-10 09:09 UTC — Opener protocol (second pass) [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #15 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Would adding a one-sentence "current state" opener protocol to Wayfinder's session-start practice collapse situation-model hedging in the first exchange — making the document stack functionally complete for all hedging types at T=0?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 15. Run #14 explored this same question but the edit didn't push, so it appeared unchecked again. Second pass deepens the finding. Supabase/Slack blocked.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+Confirmed: near-zero (not absolute zero) hedging at T=0. The precision matters.
+
+*Why not absolute zero.* Even with a perfect opener, structural uncertainty remains about: (1) exact emotional weight of words used; (2) whether the stated situation has unstated sub-elements; (3) whether the stated session mode matches the actual mode that emerges. These are small — approximately one hedging phrase per 10 exchanges — but "absolute zero" is the wrong claim. "Functional completeness" is accurate.
+
+*The two-key framing.* Document stack = Key 1 (person-model pre-saturation). Opener sentence = Key 2 (situation-model resolved at T=0). Together: session begins with near-complete shared context. Without Key 2, the session works but requires 3–5 exchanges to resolve what the opener handles in one sentence.
+
+*The minimum viable opener.* Three elements: (1) current emotional register, (2) active background context, (3) session mode. All three fit in one sentence. "I'm good, court's next month and I'm less anxious about it, want to work on the vocabulary today." — that's the template, or near enough.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+- What would a canonical opener format look like? → Added to ACTIVE.
+- Can Bones synthesize an opener when Wayfinder doesn't provide one? → Added to ACTIVE.
+
